Use tidyr::uncount() function to convert our lobster data from frequency format to case format

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>% 
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Exploratory data visualization

We’re only going to consider ‘site’ as our variable of interest

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site),
              alpha = 0.5,
              width = 0.2)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# Histogram
ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")

Convert the ‘date’ column to class ‘Date’

We’ll use the ‘lubridate’ package to convert to Date format, and then to help us easily parse month and year

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(date_new = lubridate::mdy(date))

Now lets parse year and month using lubridate::month() and lubridate::year()

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>% 
  mutate(obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
         obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new))

Now let’s find counts of observed lobsters based on different hierarchical groupings:

First: let’s count lobsters by year and month:

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(obs_year, obs_month)

lobster_y <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(obs_year)

# How many lobsters observed by site?
lobster_site <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  dplyr::count(site)

If we want to create a summary table that contains statistics OTHER than counts by group, it’s easier to use group_by() + n()

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
            lobster_number = n())

Find confidence intervals

Use t.test() function to find confidence intervals (for one sample) and perform t-tests to compare means of two samples (… this will be covered conceptually in lectures in week 6)

ivee_lobster <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobster)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobster
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

Two-sample t-test to compare means

We want to ask: Is there a significant difference in lobster lengths at Naples and Mohawk reefs?

We’ve done our necessary exploratory analyses to determine that a 2-sample t-test for means comparison is appropriate.

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mn_ttest <- t.test(mohk_sample, napl_sample)
mn_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mohk_sample and napl_sample
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.86833  78.18454

There is a significant difference in lobster lengths between Mohawk and Naples Reef (t(df) = statistic, p < 0.001, alpha = 0.05).

lobster_mn <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL", "MOHK"))

mn_ttest2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_mn)

mn_ttest2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  size_mm by site
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean in group MOHK mean in group NAPL 
##           66.86833           78.18454
mn_ttest2$p.value
## [1] 1.215408e-79
mn_ttest2$statistic
##         t 
## -19.84873
mn_ttest2$conf.int
## [1] -12.43436 -10.19806
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95

Here is the p-value: 1.215407810^{-79}

Here is my t-statistic: -19.8487322
